# Projects — Opportunity scan source of truth

Canonical operating rule for discovering, filtering, and recording funding and project opportunities for **FairBanks / FCHIP**. Applicant context: **we are Ugandans** — every listing must be something a Ugandan organisation, founder, or team member can realistically apply for.

## Deliverables

| Role | Path |
|---|---|
| Opportunity tracker (Excel) | `opportunities/opportunities.xlsx` |
| Build script (regenerate when curated data changes) | `opportunities/build_opportunities.py` |
| This rule | `opportunities/.cursor/rules/source_of_truth.mdc` |

Prefer regenerating via `python build_opportunities.py` from `opportunities/`. Keep **one** master tracker (`opportunities.xlsx`). Do not keep `ofy_*`, `*_new`, or other duplicate Excel copies beside it.

## Excel structure

**Sheet 1 — Opportunities** (required columns, in this order):

| Column | Requirement |
|---|---|
| Project Title | Official or commonly used programme name |
| URL | Direct link to the opportunity page (OFY article or official call) |
| Brief Description | Plain English; **under 101 words**; goals, eligibility, and FairBanks relevance |
| Application Deadline | Absolute date (e.g. `31 July 2026`) or `Rolling`; note timezone if stated |
| Gender Category | See gender rules below |

**Sheet 2 — Scan Notes** (required): source sites, scan date, method, eligibility filter applied, exclusions, counts by gender category, priority-soon list, and a reminder to verify deadlines on official programme pages.

Sort rows: gender-based first, then multi-gender; within each group, soonest actionable deadline first. Unknown or rolling deadlines go last.

## Gender categories

Use exactly one of:

- **Gender-based (women/girls)** — explicitly for women, girls, or women-led ventures (e.g. AWIEF Pitch n Grow, GirlCode Hackathon, UN Women programmes).
- **Multi-gender (all genders)** — open to all genders; may still encourage women but without gender as a hard requirement.

Do not invent other category labels unless the user asks to extend the schema.

## Eligibility filter (Uganda)

**Include only** opportunities that are:

1. **Still open** as of the scan date (deadline not passed; or explicitly rolling).
2. **Open to Ugandan applicants** — global calls, pan-African / African Union, Sub-Saharan Africa, East Africa, or Uganda-specific.

**Exclude** (document reason in Scan Notes):

- Country- or region-locked calls that omit Uganda (e.g. Ghana-only, India–Japan only, US-only).
- Sector locks that exclude FairBanks (e.g. game-development studios only, UK filmmakers only).
- Private consultancies, for-profit-only tenders with no NGO/social-enterprise path, or scholarships clearly ineligible for Ugandan nationals.
- Closed opportunities (deadline passed) unless the user explicitly wants a historical archive.

When eligibility is ambiguous, verify on the **official programme page** before including. If still unclear, exclude and note in Scan Notes.

## Scan method

For each target site below, perform a **deep scan**:

1. Homepage and category/listing pages (grants, fellowships, jobs, conferences, competitions, Africa/regional filters).
2. Individual listing pages for candidates that might fit FairBanks (HealthTech, digital health, community health, AI-for-good, women-led deep tech, Uganda health systems, youth/community programmes).
3. Live verification of deadline and eligibility on the listing and, where possible, the official funder page.

If bulk crawl hits rate limits (e.g. HTTP 429), use targeted page fetches and site search rather than skipping verification.

## FairBanks / FCHIP fit (prioritisation)

When curating or ordering opportunities, favour calls aligned with:

- Community health intelligence, CHW/VHT data, digital health, disease surveillance, maternal and child health.
- Women-led deep technology (AWIEF theme: **Deep Roots. Digital Futures.**).
- Uganda health-system strengthening, district health, NGO/social-enterprise grants.
- AI-for-good, GovTech, and capacity-building that supports FCHIP team or pilots.

Mark strongest fits in descriptions; do not drop relevant opportunities solely because fit is indirect.

